<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06079053 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06079053 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Walesa  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  POLAND; PRESIDENT; TRAVEL; US; FOREIGN; RELATION; INDUSTRY; MARKETING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  President Lech Walesa left today for a one-week tour of the United States tothank Americans for their support of Polish reforms and to invite U.S.businesses to set up shop in Poland's new free-market system.;    It wasWalesa's first foreign trip since being sworn in as head of state Dec. 22,with the exception of a quick visit to the Vatican to visit Polish-born PopeJohn Paul II.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WALESA COURTS U.S. BUSINESSES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Walesa was accompanied by Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski,Privatization Minister Jan Lewandowski and Foreign Trade Minister DariuszLewordowski.;    &quot;First of all I will give thanks for the help,&quot; Walesa said.&quot;Secondly, I will point out that the whole world is counting on the UnitedStates.&quot;;    Strong U.S. backing helped Poland win an unprecedented 50 percentreduction of its debt with creditor nations. They announced the debt reductionFriday.;    Poland owed $33.5 billion to European nations because of debts runup in the 1970s by the country's former Communist rulers. The country's totalforeign debt, however, is $48.5 billion, including money owed to banks, Sovietbloc nations, international groups and private businesses.;    While in theUnited States, Walesa also will try to encourage American companies to investin Poland, which has lagged behind smaller Hungary and Czechoslovakia inattracting Western businesses.;    &quot;To help does not mean to give money,&quot; saidWalesa. &quot;We have the technical means and natural resources and it can all bearranged in such a way that you may achieve big results with a little input.&quot;;   He is to start his trip visiting with President Bush at the White Houseearly Wednesday. He will then meet with U.S. officials and congressionalrepresentatives over the following two days.;    On Friday, Walesa travels toLos Angeles where he meets with former President Reagan.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Warsaw, Poland  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910319  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  298  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 19, 199100079053,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>